    <h2>Brandenburg Concerto No. 5 in D major, movement III</h2>
    <h3>Context</h3>
    <p>
        - Bach was a major composer of the Baroque period (and ever).<br>
        - Innovator in forms and structures still used and developed today.<br>
        - Brandenburg Concerto No.5 is part of a set of six concertos, dedicated to the Margrave of Brandenburg. It is
        an example of the concerto grosso form.
    </p>
    <br>
    <h3>Sonority</h3>
    <p>
        - Harpsichord, violin, flute, cello, double bass, orchestra combine to create a bright, intricate Baroque palette that feels energetic yet refined.<br>
        - Solo (concertino) – violino principale, flauto, cembalo concertato – provides virtuosic contrast that heightens drama and keeps the listener focused.<br>
        - Ripieno – Violono di ripieno, viola da ripieno, violoncello, contrabasso – reinforce harmony and add warmth, giving the tutti passages a rich, full-bodied statement that balances the soloists.
    </p>
    <br>
    <h3>Structure</h3>
    <p>
        - ABA (ternary) form gives the movement familiarity, so the return of A feels satisfying and reassuring.<br>
        - The two main ideas in A create distinct yet related moods: the first subject is lively and assertive, while the second is more graceful, adding contrast.<br>
        - The B section develops the first subject, introducing tension and variation before the comforting return of A.
    </p>
    <br>
    <h3>Texture</h3>
    <p>
        - Polyphonic + contrapuntal writing makes the music feel woven and sophisticated, reflecting Baroque complexity.<br>
        - The fugal opening gives a sense of order and momentum as each entry joins the texture.<br>
        - The solo violin’s subject followed by the flute’s answer builds suspense through imitation.<br>
        - The harpsichord answers itself, expanding the texture and intensifying the interplay between voices.<br>
        - Once all four parts join, the counterpoint feels full and majestic, highlighting the contrapuntal mastery.<br>
        - Flute and violin doubling adds brilliance and clarity in moments like bar 33.<br>
        - The tonic pedal in the bass of the middle section grounds the harmonic shift and keeps the atmosphere anchored while the theme evolves.
    </p>
    <br>
    <h3>Melody</h3>
    <p>
        - Mostly conjunct lines give a graceful, flowing effect, while occasional leaps (such as fourths) inject excitement.<br>
        - Scalaped extensions in the harpsichord keep the solo writing lively and virtuosic.<br>
        - The rising sequence at bar 137 builds intensity just before the return of A.<br>
        - Ornaments, including trills, add sparkle and expressiveness typical of Baroque elegance.
    </p>
    <br>
    <h3>Harmony and Tonality</h3>
    <p>
        - Centered on D major, the music feels bright and triumphant for most of the movement.<br>
        - Dissonances add brief tension, keeping the harmonic language expressive.<br>
        - The B section’s modulation to A major and B minor introduces warmth and contrast before returning home.<br>
        - Functional diatonic harmony with I, IV, V (and occasional ii, vi) keeps the progression clear and satisfying.<br>
        - Root position and first inversion chords create stability, while perfect cadences mark clear sectional endings.<br>
        - Occasional suspensions (e.g., 9-8 at bar 130) add emotional colour by delaying resolution.
    </p>
    <br>
    <h3>TRaM</h3>
    <p>
        - The duple 2/4 pulse (or implied 6/8) gives the movement a sprightly, dance-like gigue feel.<br>
        - Fast semiquaver runs in the harpsichord fuel momentum and excitement.<br>
        - Triplets and dotted rhythms add rhythmic flair, ensuring the movement feels buoyant and energetic throughout.
    </p>
