    <h2>Beethoven Pathétique 1st Movement</h2>
    <h3>Context</h3>
    <p>
        - In the classical period, the harpsichord was replaced by the piano.<br>
        - The decline in use of the continuo as the middle-range instruments such as clarinets and horns were used in
        the orchestra to fill out the harmonies.<br>
        - More instruments were added to the standard orchestra. The symphony rose to prominence as the main type of
        concert music played by
        these increasingly large orchestras.<br>
        - Ludwig van Beethoven was born in 1770 in Bonn (west Germany). As a young man he moved to Vienna, where he
        became a virtuoso pianist.
        ‘Virtuoso’ means displaying skill and agility in difficult music.<br>
        - Beethoven was a crucial figure in the transition between the Classical and Romantic periods of music history.
        His music is often seen as
        embodying the ideals of the Romantic period, such as emotional expression and individualism.
    </p>
    <br>
    <h3>Structure</h3>
    <p>
        - The first movement is sonata form, a structure used in the first and sometimes last movements of sonatas,
        symphonies and other Classical works.<br>
        - Sonata form is intro → exposition (1st (tonic key) and 2nd, (dominant key) subject) → development (builds on
        exposition) →
        recapitulation (1st, tonic and 2nd, also tonic subject) → coda.<br>
        - The movement begins with a slow introduction, which is not typical of sonata form.<br>
        - When the exposition is entered a chromatic scale is played.
        <ul>
            <li>Very, very slow (grave :skull:) intro (bars 1-10).</li>
            <li>Exposition 1<sup>st</sup> subject, fast (bars 11-50).</li>
            <li>Exposition 2<sup>nd</sup> subject - Long High Notes (bars 51-132).</li>
            <li>Repeat exposition, end is alternating high-low chords and a pause.</li>
            <li>Development (bars 133-194): slow intro repeats at the start, but in a different key.</li>
            <li>Recapitulation (bars 195-294).</li>
            <li>Coda (bars 295-end): goes to intro again, ends with basically slamming the piano.</li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <br>
    <h3>Sonority</h3>
    <p>
        - When Beethoven wrote this piece at the end of the 18th century, the piano had almost completely replaced the
        harpsichord as the keyboard instrument of choice for the home and concert hall.<br>
        - It was known as the fortepiano. ‘Piano’ is the Italian term for ‘soft’. ‘Forte’: ‘loud’. It was now possible
        to play using all kinds of dynamic levels just by altering the pressure of the fingers on the keys. 
        This was not possible on the harpsichord.<br>
        - Mozart and Haydn had started to use dynamic markings, but Beethoven was one of the first to make extensive use
        of all kinds of dynamic possibilities. This makes the piece particularly expressive and emotional.<br>
        - This sonata has frequent crescendos, diminuendos and numerous other performance markings.<br>
        - There is some inclusion of <i>fortepiano</i> (fp) markings, where a note is played loudly and then immediately
        softly, creating great constrast, and only really possible on the piano at the time.<br>
        - The sustaining pedal was coming into use at the time and was sometimes worked by the knees instead of by the
        foot. This was not notated but Beethoven would have followed some kind of system in his performances.<br>
        - The piano part is virtuosic, with wide leaps, fast scales and arpeggios, and dramatic dynamic contrasts.
    </p>
    <br>
    <h3>Melody</h3>
    <p>
        - The six-note motif in the slow intro casts an anticipatory, mysterious atmosphere that keeps the listener on edge, especially when it is reduced to five notes or turns upward instead of downward.<br>
        - The scalic passages, including the descending chromatic scale at the end of the intro and the ascending tonic scale with raised third in the first subject, create restless tension that resolves into a triumphant but uneasy mood with the distinctive augmented second (Ab to B#) adding drama.<br>
        - Bursting arpeggios and broken chords (bars 29-30) drop quickly, producing a exhilarated, forward-moving pulse that heightens excitement.<br>
        - Ornaments around the second subject (acciaccaturas, mordents, trills) add glittering, nervy energy that colors the recap with heightened urgency.
    </p>
    <br>
    <h3>TRaM</h3>
    <p>
        - The grave, common-time introduction gives a solemn, ominous atmosphere that contrasts with the liveliness that follows.<br>
        - Dotted rhythms (bar 1) reinforce the stately, dramatic mood of the opening gesture.<br>
        - Rapid figures such as septuplets and 1/128th notes in bar 10 inject fleeting bursts of agitation before the allegro.<br>
        - The allegro di molto e con brio ("very fast and with vigor") 
        in cut time thrusts the movement into vibrant, kinetic energy, driving the listener forward.<br>
        - Continuous quavers under the first subject add relentless propulsion, while staccato crotchets in the right hand puncture 
        the texture with bright, assertive attacks.
    </p>
    <br>
    <h3>Texture</h3>
    <p>
        - The homophonic writing in the intro (e.g., bar 1) produces a dense, solemn atmosphere, with octaves later rising the emotion.<br>
        - The long descending monophonic line before the recap (bars 187-194) deepens the sense of introspection, then the melody-and-accompaniment homophony of the second subject feels warm and resolved.<br>
        - Two-part passages with broken chords (bar 93) and the brief passage in thirds leading into the final trills layer soothing yet lively colours, balancing intimacy with brilliance.
    </p>
    <br>
    <h3>Harmony</h3>
    <p>
        <p>
            <strong>Typical Classical/Romantic features:</strong><br>
            - Chromatic chords such as diminished sevenths (halfway through bar 1) and augmented sixths (bars 30 and 34) lend a tense, expressive atmosphere before release.<br>
            - Perfect cadences throughout give a sense of confident closure that keeps the overall mood grounded.<br>
            - Circle-of-fifths passages (bars 244–249) spin the motion forward with noble sweep.
        </p>
        <p>
            <strong>Less typical/contrastive feature:</strong><br>
            - The interrupted cadence in the introduction (bar 9) holds back momentum, creating suspense that makes the main tempo’s arrival feel triumphant.
        </p>
    </p>
    <br>
    <h3>Tonality</h3>
    <p>
        - C minor provides a dramatic, brooding backdrop for the entire movement.<br>
        - Modulations to related keys such as E♭ major and F minor brighten the mood intermittently, offering hope before the return to C minor.<br>
        - The shift to unrelated keys like E minor during the development introduces surprise and restlessness, enhancing the adventurous spirit of the drama.
    </p>
